difficulty with lack of in person engagement with friends; a lot of work as my husband is a small business owner

mostly positively - despite kids needing to attend school from home, our life pace has slowed down, we have spent a lot of time with our neighbors, I have appreciated the slower pace

daughter's wedding postponed. No normal family visiting.
not travelling and being able to go where I want with the limited time I have really sucks

I tend to be an introvert.  Working from home is welcomed.  I'm still able to grocery shop.  I choose not to attend in person church services.  So I don't really feel the impact like others do, esp those who are more extroverted.

Mostly social/activities outside the home.  I can be a hermit, so I am not suffering as much as an extrovert might.    Early in the pandemic, I was anxious about grocery shopping and finding what we needed.  That has been resolved.
Not able to send as much time out side of the home.
Miss seeing & hugging children & grandchildren.  Worry a little that a positive diagnosis will delay medical cancer treatments or hinder recovery.

We have stopped full time travel and are sequestered on a100 acre farm in southwest Washington. We are very busy working on the farm and our presence has made their lives as well as ours immeasurably better. They provided us shelter and we helped with their overwhelming work load with their 80 animals, gardening, milking and cheese making. But one of the owners is bipolar and this could end precipitously and we have nowhere else very easy to go because we gave up our home to travel fulltime.  Yikes. We feel lucky beyond measure to be here but know it could just end.

1) Attempts to move family member to Assisted Living has been very difficult and stressful.  2) In the middle of home improvement project when coronavirus lockdown occurred.  Continue to feel worried about having contracters in home so house remains topsy turvy.
